Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: The Downtown Arts District: From the city’s most innovative and celebrated chefs, to galleries of every ilk, trailblazing academia in architecture & design, and downtown’s largest massing of tech and culture-forward workforce, this dense, just-off-the-beaten-path neighborhood offers the best of the new urban Los Angeles.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: rd & Garey is 27,000 SF of iconic brick and bow-truss space in the most mature retail district of the Arts District. A former lightbulb manufactory erected in 1905, the property was thoughtfully refurbished in2016. The reinforced masonry with industrious skylights, striking bow-truss and window-line galore is ready to house the next generation of purveyors and tastemakers.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: In LA’s one-of-a-kind Arts District, a new project is seeking to reflect the past while building new spaces for the future. Third & Traction is located on the same corner as the historic Joel Bloom Square and is fueled by the same passion for community that made Mr. Bloom a legend in this neighborhood. Low rise, yet distinctively urban and industrial, Third & Traction is an inviting mixed-use complex that seeks to provide intimate places for residents and community members alike to sit, share, and create. Meet your neighbors and generate fresh ideas in this community that is reimagining the line between public and private space.

Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text: A neighborhood that has defined an entire region, Hollywood has shown many faces. From the Golden Era of Hollywood in the 20s through the 60s, to the gritty charm of 70s and 80s, even the tourist-laden 90s and aughts, this iconic centerpiece has always been abuzz with life and activity. Common.LocationDescription.Common.Text:
Larchmont Village Shopping District, the heart of affluent and historic Hancock Park, has long been recognized as the hidden gem of Los Angeles. 
As one of the only, and perhaps the original, high-traffic pedestrian retail streets in the city, it’s a classic intersection of contemporary trend-setting and 
homegrown sincerity.

Common.LongDescription.Common.Text: Larchmont Mercantile is the most distinctive project on the street, located on the best block in the Village. It offers the largest contiguous street frontage in the neighborhood which, beyond generating a cohesive vision to the built environment, also plays a key role in representing the Larchmont Village Shopping District’s future. With 14 contiguous retail stores and 4 unique architectural facades, Larchmont Mercantile features generously-sized storefronts and shallow 60-foot bay depths. It spans over more than 17,000 square feet of commercial space, with storefronts that range in size from 993 to 1,311 square feet. The Larchmont Mercantile offers signage and secured rear entrances for each retail store, as well as a spacious parking lot inclusive of ~60 parking spaces with valet assist and an entrance just adjacent. The scale and walkability of the Larchmont Village Shopping District reinforces the experience of a unique small town gem.
